    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-23T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-23T03:00:00-05:00" n="536"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d536">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6599: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-23T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 23, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 23—2:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>170. Grant Forbes called on me today. He brought a letter from his [uncle]
                    Cameron Forbes.<note n="86" xml:id="d536fn86">Former Ambassador in Japan.</note>
                    I do not know whom he represents but believe that he is working with and for a
                    financial group of which Jean Monnet<note n="87" xml:id="d536fn87">French
                        banker.</note> and T. V. Soong have been dominating and moving spirits.
                    Forbes stated that he had been discussing with Kung possibilities of a material
                    credit arrangement which I believe was based on China’s holdings of silver, but
                    that Kung had made conditions so difficult that he thought his principals would
                    not approve. Forbes stated he was awaiting reply to a telegram. He suggested to
                    me that American Government might be well advised to grant Chinese forces aid in
                    the form of munitions. I told Forbes that I saw no chance of <pb facs="0530"
                        n="526" xml:id="pg_526"/> this; that furthermore I had on all occasions
                    attempted to make quite clear to the Chinese that they could not expect any such
                    aid from American sources.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
